## Q1. Experimental setting; relation between $\beta$ and the predictors; Bayesian baselines

**On clarity of the setting.** We agree the description was too compressed. The
relationship between the coefficients and the side information --- which is the
quantity of interest --- is specified in Appendix B.2 but not stated where the
reader first needs it.

\rev{Revision: Section 5.2 now states the generative mechanism inline. In the
known-groups design, predictors are partitioned into five groups and
$\beta_j \sim \pi_{0,k(j)}\delta_0 + (1-\pi_{0,k(j)})\mathcal{N}(0,
\sigma^2_{s,k(j)})$, so that group membership determines both sparsity and signal
magnitude (Table 4). In the continuous-index design, $t_j \sim
\mathrm{Unif}(0,3)$ and $\beta_j = 0$ on two null bands, with $\beta_j \sim
\mathcal{N}(0, \sigma(t_j)^2)$ elsewhere, $\sigma(t) = 0.01 + |\sin(\pi t)|$.
The side information is $d_j = $ one-hot group indicator and $d_j = t_j$
respectively.}

**On sparsity patterns.** The reviewer writes that we vary signal magnitude but
not the sparsity pattern. This is accurate for the *baseline comparison* of
Section 5.1, which reuses the design of Kim et al. (2024) --- but not for
Section 5.2, where $\pi_0$ varies across groups from $1.00$ (fully null) to
$0.00$ (dense), and where the continuous-index design has structurally zero
regions. That said, the reviewer's underlying point stands: in Section 5.1 the
side information carries no information by construction, so Nash cannot separate
from mr.ash there, and that section is better understood as a check that Nash
loses nothing in the no-side-information regime than as a demonstration of the
method.

\rev{Revision: Section 5.1 is now explicitly framed as a null-side-information
sanity check, and we have added a design in which sparsity structure --- not
merely amplitude --- varies with $d_j$ at fixed marginal sparsity, isolating the
structural signal.} \rev{[TODO: new Table 10.]}

**On frequentist baselines.** We accept this criticism. Lasso and Elastic Net
treat $\beta$ as fixed and are not directly comparable as inference procedures,
even if they are the standard predictive baselines in this literature (and the
ones used by Kim et al. 2024, which is why we adopted them). We have added
Bayesian competitors:

- **Horseshoe** and **regularised horseshoe** (global--local shrinkage, no side
  information);
- **Spike-and-slab with group-level hyperpriors**, which is the natural Bayesian
  analogue of Nash in the known-groups setting and the closest existing method
  that uses the same side information;
- **mr.ash**, already included, which is itself an empirical Bayes procedure.

\rev{[TODO: results --- new Table 11, both synthetic settings and all four real
datasets.]}

The spike-and-slab-with-group-hyperpriors comparison is the informative one: it
shares Nash's modelling assumption in the grouped case and differs only in how
the prior is parameterised and fitted. We expect comparable accuracy there and a
large computational gap; the continuous-index and graph settings are where the
neural parameterisation is not straightforwardly replaced.

