## Q3. Novelty relative to hierarchical Bayes

The reviewer is right that covariate-dependent priors are not new, and our
framing did not acknowledge this adequately. We have rewritten Section 2 to make
the claim narrower and, we hope, defensible.

**What is not new.** Making the prior depend on covariate-level features is
standard in hierarchical Bayesian modelling. Relevant precedents include
annotation-informed priors in statistical genetics, Bayesian group and fused
lassos (Casella et al. 2010; Betancourt et al. 2017), hierarchical spike-and-slab
models with group-level hyperparameters, and the broader literature on
structured shrinkage. \rev{Revision: these are now cited and discussed in
Section 2 rather than treated as absent.}

**What we claim is new.** Not the model class, but the estimation strategy that
makes an *arbitrary neural parameterisation* of that prior tractable in the
$p \gg n$ regime without MCMC and without cross-validation. Specifically:

- Existing hierarchical approaches either impose a conjugate or low-dimensional
  hyperprior (so the M-step is closed-form) or resort to MCMC (so the cost is
  prohibitive at $p \sim 10^5$). Neither accommodates $g(\cdot; d_j, \theta)$
  with $\theta$ the weights of an MLP or GNN.
- Direct CAVI on such a model couples prior learning to every coordinate
  update: $\hat\beta_{j,\mathrm{MLE}}$ changes whenever any other coordinate
  changes, so $\hat\theta$ must be refit after each one --- $\mathcal{O}(p)$
  backward passes per sweep (Corollary A.7).
- Split VEB removes this coupling via a latent Gaussian layer, giving one
  batched M-step per sweep regardless of $p$.

The contribution, then, is that a familiar modelling idea becomes computable at
a scale and with a prior flexibility where it previously was not. \rev{Section 2
now states this as the contribution, and the Discussion no longer claims novelty
for the covariate-dependent prior itself.}

